Register  Now


Faculty | Schedule | Registration | Location | Sponsorship | Audio Package |   

Multiples are way up among food and nutrition  companies -- often 10x EBITDA and more -- reflecting consumers' insatiable demand  for good-for-you foods. 
 
And because this trend is being driven by Millennials,  it's only going to get bigger in 2015.
 
There are specific niches growing in double digits,  springing from changing buying patterns that favor smaller entrepreneurial  brands. Change is coming from the bottom up, and consumers' new demands have  not been met quickly enough by the large multinationals.
 
Middle-market companies are meeting the appetite  for more protein-rich foods. For more on-the-go snacks and meals. For less fat  and fewer additives, for all-organic and zero GMOs. Many specialty brands once  targeted to athletes, bodybuilders, and other limited audiences are now finding  their way onto mainstream store shelves.
 
Combine these appealing characteristics with  today's low interest rates and relatively low compliance impacts on the middle  market, and you have an industry that presents huge opportunities in 2015. 
 
 Helping you succeed  in this changing marketplace is what The Capital Roundtable’s ENCORE conference  -- “Private Equity Investing in Food & Nutrition Companies” -- is all about. It's being held in New  York City on Thursday, April 30.
 
Here Are Four Reasons Why You Should Join Us
 

Hear  which exotic ingredients are driving innovation on grocery shelves.
Understand  which products are taking market share from traditional carbonated sodas,  carb-laden snacks, and artificially-flavored convenience foods. 
Discover  the expanding categories such as baby food, protein based snacks, and non GMO  products where disruptive technology is creating new winners and losers.
Learn  about the mainstreaming of functional foods and beverages -- how consumers are  demanding foods that not only deliver on taste but also do more nutritionally  for them -- and how growth comes when you can deliver on both.

 
Register Now to Get Expert Advice from Sarah Ashmore Bradley
 
Chairing our conference is Sarah Ashmore  Bradley, a founding partner at Kainos Capital, a middle market private  equity firm exclusively focusing on the food and consumer products. 
 
Kainos has invested over $2 billion and is one  of the most active private equity firms having completed four deals over the  past year. The firm’s strategy is to build a diversified portfolio of  strategically relevant companies that trade buyers would like to acquire. 
 
Sarah brings over 15 years of  food and consumer products investment banking and private equity experience.  She was a managing director at Investcorp  where she spent three years as head of global IR and fundraising. Previously,  she was a managing director at Deutsche Bank and a director in Citigroup’s Global Markets. 
 
Sarah earned  degrees in business administration and professional accounting the University  of Texas and is a CPA.  She is a director of Milk Specialties Global,  InterHealth Nutraceuticals, Fempro, and JTM Foods.  
 
Click  here to receive your best rate -- a savings of $400 on our regular conference rates.
 
Register Now to Meet More Than 20 Experts 
On Investing in Private Food & Nutrition Companies
 
This conference brings you the newest and most  rewarding developments in the food and nutrition industry, covering  opportunities in branded products, private label, nutraceuticals, sports  nutrition, and more. In addition, our panelists will answer important questions  such as --

How can private equity investors  best compete with strategics, and justify the expense of a sought-after food  and nutrition deal? 
What metrics and valuation  guidelines can help you judge a middle-market food and nutrition company deal? 
What are the ramifications of the  rise in ecommerce grocery sales, and which companies are best positioned to  exploit this channel? 
How can you take advantage of the  shift toward functional foods, where consumers substitute fortified products  for supplements and even medicine? 
What  are the most important things a firm has to get right when exiting a food and  nutrition investment? 
Will mothers of young children  continue to be the guiding force behind product innovations such as Greek  yogurt and squeezable packaging? 
How are food and nutrition  companies differentiating themselves through social media and through  nutritional-focused smart phone apps? 
What changes are ahead in the  snack bar category, and which new ingredients and food dayparts are soon to  become prominent? 
How are food and nutrition  companies adapting to expanding consumer preferences for gels, chews, bites,  shots and other on-the-go formulations? 
What are the best practices for  overseeing food and nutrition portfolio companies?

Five More Reasons Why You Should Join Us 
 

Learn  which legacy brands and categories are in free fall and which private label  categories are growing.  
Find  why so many industry experts foresee a huge boom ahead in nuts, chia, hemp, and  related ingredients.  
Realize  what lies ahead for commodity prices and how manufacturers are managing their  costs of goods sold. 
Learn  about expanding categories outside of the nutrition category -- like snack  pies.
Find  out about investing in the ingredient companies that supply the large  multinationals, when multiples are too high to invest in the brands themselves.


 
